tp:treatment-sec.p:
Distribution. BELIZE . GUATEMALA . MEXICO : States of Chiapas , Colima , Guanajuato , Guerrero , Jalisco , Michoacán , Morelos , Nayarit , Nuevo León , Oaxaca , Sinaloa . UNITET STATES OF AMERICA: Texas. Many of these records are not supported with deposited material in collections and have no specific localities ( Quintero, 1981 ; Armas 2006b ;
Armas et al., 2014
). ( Fig. 18 ).

Diagnosis.
Phrynus operculatus
can be distinguished from other species of the genus by the presence of the following set of characters: only one conspicuous tooth in the ectal row of the base of chelicerae, with an acuminated apex (
Fig. 1F
), does not present an inconspicuous spine in the dorsomedial area of the pedipalp tarsus, Pd2 is smaller than Pd4, Fv3 smaller than Fv5, Td1 is very small but longer than Td4 (
Fig. 2
). Female genitalia have tubular and elongated gonopod bases, with claw-like sclerites of the gonopod, curved at the apical region (
Fig. 17A
). In the male genitalia, the ornamentations over LoL 1 and 2 are tubular and long, and LoD is very thick and pronounced (
Fig. 3
). Almost the wide of the base of LoL 1 (
Table 6
).

Chelicera.
The mesal row of the basal segment of chelicerae with three teeth, the first is bilobed, placed in the proximal portion, lobe 1b bigger than 1a, followed by one tooth shorter in medial portion, and the third, bigger than the others, placed in the distal region (
Fig. 1D
). The ectal row with one conspicuous tooth (tooth 2) with an acuminated apex, placed in the medial region. There is a small keel on the most proximal region (tooth 1) (
Fig. 1F
). The mobile segment of chelicerae with four teeth, the first one is the biggest, followed by the third, and the fourth is the smallest.
